HEADWORD: Wreak
<hw>Wreak</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To reck; to
care.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wreak
<hw>Wreak</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Wreaked</conjf> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Wreaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wreken</ets> to revenge, punish, drive out, AS. <ets>wrecan</ets>;
akin to OFries. <ets>wreka</ets>, OS. <ets>wrekan</ets> to punish, D.
<ets>wreken</ets> to avenge, G. <ets>r⟦aum⟧chen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>rehhan</ets>, Icel. <ets>reka</ets> to drive, to take vengeance,
Goth. <ets>wrikan</ets> to persecute, Lith. <ets>vargas</ets> distress,
<ets>vargti</ets> to suffer distress, L. <ets>urgere</ets> to drive,
urge, Gr. <grk>e'i`rgein</grk> to shut, Skr. <ets>v⟦rsdot⟧j</ets> to
turn away. Cf. <er>Urge</er>, <er>Wreck</er>,
<er>Wretch</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To revenge; to avenge.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He should <qex>wreake</qex> him on his foes.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Another's wrongs to <qex>wreak</qex> upon thyself.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come <qex>wreak</qex> his loss, whom bootless ye complain.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inflict or execute, especially in vengeance or
passion; to hurl or drive; <as>as, to <ex>wreak</ex> vengeance on an
enemy; to <ex>wreak</ex> havoc</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>The word <i>wrought</i> is sometimes assumed to be the past
tense of <ex>wreak</ex>, as the phrases <col><b>wreak havoc</b></col>
and <col><b>wrought havoc</b></col> are both commonly used. In fact,
<col><b>wrought havoc</b></col> is not as common as <col><b>wreaked
havoc</b></col>. Whether <i>wrought</i> is considered as the past tense
of wreak or of work, <col><b>wrought havoc</b></col> has essentially the
same meaning. Etymologically, however, <i>wrought</i> is only the past
tense of <i>work</i>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>On me let Death <qex>wreak</qex> all his rage.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now was the time to be avenged on his old enemy, to
<qex>wreak</qex> a grudge of seventeen years.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But gather all thy powers,⟦br⟧
And <qex>wreak</qex> them on the verse that thou dost weave.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wreak
<hw>Wreak</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>wr⟦ae⟧c</ets> exile,
persecution, misery. See <er>Wreak</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<def>Revenge; vengeance; furious passion; resentment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak. Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreaken</ent>⟦br⟧
